    <a href="/reading/proof-writing/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to proofs</a>

    <h1>Cardinality</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Jim Hefferon · GFDL + CC BY-SA 2.5 · <a href="https://hefferon.net/">Introduction to Proofs</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Two sets have the same <strong>cardinality</strong> when there is a bijection between them. The natural numbers and the even numbers have the same cardinality (both countably infinite). But the real numbers have strictly larger cardinality. Cantor proved this with his <strong>diagonal argument</strong>.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SVG: Cantor's diagonal argument -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 340 240" class="w-full max-w-sm" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Title -->
        <text x="170" y="18" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.5">Cantor's diagonal argument</text>
        <!-- Grid of digits -->
        <text x="60" y="50" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.4">r1 = 0.</text>
        <text x="115" y="50" fill="#f87171" font-size="12" font-weight="bold">5</text>
        <text x="130" y="50" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.4">1 7 0 3 ...</text>

        <text x="60" y="75" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.4">r2 = 0.</text>
        <text x="115" y="75" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.4">3</text>
        <text x="130" y="75" fill="#f87171" font-size="12" font-weight="bold">9</text>
        <text x="145" y="75" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.4">2 8 4 ...</text>

        <text x="60" y="100" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.4">r3 = 0.</text>
        <text x="115" y="100" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.4">7 4</text>
        <text x="145" y="100" fill="#f87171" font-size="12" font-weight="bold">1</text>
